ingredientsDetail.description: Allulose is a low calorie artificial sweetener with a similar taste and texture to sugar. ingredientsDetail.name: Allulose

ingredientsDetail.description: Aspartame is an artificial sweetener made from two amino acids (the building blocks of protein), phenylalanine and aspartic acid. Aspartame is commonly used as a table top sweetener under the brand names Nutrasweet and Equal. Aspartame is not thought to affect blood sugar levels and may be a better alternative to table sugar for diabetics.
ingredientsDetail.name: Aspartame

ingredientsDetail.description: Azodicarbonamide (ADA) is used as a dough conditioner in breads and as a whitener in cereal flours.
ingredientsDetail.name: Azodicarbonamide

ingredientsDetail.description: BHA or butylated hydroxyanisole is a synthetic antioxidant added to foods as a preservative.
ingredientsDetail.name: Bha

ingredientsDetail.description: BHT or butylated hydroxytoluene is a synthetic antioxidant added to foods to prevent rancidity and is also found in food packaging.
ingredientsDetail.name: Bht

ingredientsDetail.description: Blue #1 is a synthetic food dye commonly used in processed foods including sugary cereals, candies, frostings, icings, ice cream, and popsicles.
ingredientsDetail.name: Blue #1

ingredientsDetail.description: Blue #2 is a synthetic food dye commonly used in processed foods including baked goods, sugary cereals, candies, ice cream, and pet food.
ingredientsDetail.name: Blue #2

ingredientsDetail.description: Brominated vegetable oil (BVO) is a food additive that stabilizes the flavors in fruit-flavored beverages including sports drink and sodas. In the 1977, the FDA changed BVO from "safe" to "interim" status, meaning it is only allowed in small quantities until further research.
ingredientsDetail.name: Brominated vegetable oil

ingredientsDetail.description: Carrageenan is a food additive made from seaweed that is often used as a thickening agent or stabilizer. Sensitive people, including those with IBS and SIBO, may experience increased GI symptoms as a result of eating carrageenan.
ingredientsDetail.name: Carrageenan

ingredientsDetail.description: Cellulose is a complex carbohydrate used as a thickener and is commonly found in cheese products and medications/supplements. Cellulose occurs naturally in plant foods and is the main constituent of cell walls in plants. Modified cellulose, commonly made from wood pulp and used as a food additive, may contribute to GI symptoms in individuals with sensitive digestive systems, such as IBS or SIBO.
ingredientsDetail.name: Cellulose

ingredientsDetail.description: Please review the ingredient and allergen statements carefully to determine which dairy ingredients are in or cross-contaminated with this product.
ingredientsDetail.name: Dairy

ingredientsDetail.description: Datem (diacetyltartaric acid esters of monoglycerides) is a dough conditioner. Dough conditioners are added to doughs to strengthen or improve texture. There is a wide variety of dough conditioners used commercially ranging from more natural ingredients like vitamin C and enzymes to artificial additives.
ingredientsDetail.name: Datem

ingredientsDetail.description: Erythritol is a sugar alcohol that is used commercially as a sugar substitute. It is often found combined with other sugar substitutes like stevia or monk fruit. It has no net carbohydrates and no effect on glucose levels, so it may be a safe alternative to table sugar for people with diabetes. It is also popular on keto diets. Erythritol is generally well absorbed in the small intestines so is less likely than other sugar alcohols to cause GI symptoms.
ingredientsDetail.name: Erythritol

ingredientsDetail.description: Ester gums, or glycerol of esters, is a food additive made from wood rosin, often used commerically in chewing gum and beverages.
ingredientsDetail.name: Ester gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Five Spice can be made up of multiple ingredients including cinnamon, cloves, fennel seeds, star anise, cloves, ginger, white pepper, and/or Sichuan peppercorns.
ingredientsDetail.name: Five spice

ingredientsDetail.description: Gellan gum is a common food additive in processed foods. It is generally considered as safe with no toxic effects studied, though it may cause GI side effects in those with sensitive digestive systems such as IBS or SIBO.
ingredientsDetail.name: Gellan gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Please review the ingredient and allergen statements carefully to determine if gluten was used to produce or came into cross-contact with this product.
ingredientsDetail.name: Gluten

ingredientsDetail.description: Natural flavors are flavor blends created by food manufacturers. They can be made from animal or plant sources including spices, fruits, vegetables, juices, yeast, herbs, dairy products, meat, poultry, seafood, eggs, bark, buds, root leaves, or plant material. The only way to determine specific ingredients in natural flavors is to contact the food manufacturer. Fig is calling on manufacturers to tell us every ingredient. Sign the pledge at everyingredient.org.
ingredientsDetail.name: Gluten free natural flavor

ingredientsDetail.description: Glycerol is a sugar alcohol derived from animal products, plants, or petroleum and is commonly used as a humectant, thickener or sweetener in processed foods. Glycerol is added to foods like beverages, protein bars, frozen yogurts, and ice cream, as well as medications and supplements. It is better absorbed in the intestine than other sugar alcohols thus less likely to cause diarrhea or other GI side effects, unless consumed in large quantities.
ingredientsDetail.name: Glycerol

ingredientsDetail.description: Green #3, or Fast Green FCF, is a synthetic food dye used in processed foods including candies, beverages, and ice cream.
ingredientsDetail.name: Green #3

ingredientsDetail.description: Guar gum is a soluble fiber made from the guar bean. It can cause increased GI symptoms in those with sensitive digestive systems, such as IBS or SIBO. High doses of guar gum used as a supplement may reduce cholesterol and glucose levels.
ingredientsDetail.name: Guar gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Gum base is an indigestible combination of food grade polymers, waxes, and softeners that gives chewing gum its chewy texture.
ingredientsDetail.name: Gum base

ingredientsDetail.description: High fructose corn syrup (HFCS) is an artificial sweetener made from corn starch. On food labels, it can be found under multiple names including glucose-fructose, isoglucose, and fructose-glucose syrups.
ingredientsDetail.name: High fructose corn syrup

ingredientsDetail.description: Hydrogenated starch hydrolysates (HSH) is an artificial sugar alcohol often made from corn starch but may also be made from potato or wheat. Commercially, HSH can be used in processed foods to help retain moisture, aid in bulking, or act as a reduced calorie sweetener. HSH may cause a laxative effect in large quantities. People with sensitive digestive systems, such as IBS or SIBO, may be more prone to experiencing GI side effects even when consuming small quantities.
ingredientsDetail.name: Hydrogenated starch hydrolysates

ingredientsDetail.description: Hydrogenated oils are made when hydrogen molecules are added to a vegetable oil to make it solid.
ingredientsDetail.name: Hydrogenated vegetable oil

ingredientsDetail.description: Inositol is a type of carbohydrate that is considered to be "vitamin-like." Inositol provides cell structure in the body, stimulates brain neurotransmitters related to mood and cognition, and helps with blood sugar control. Inositol occurs naturally in some foods, and some is produced in the body.
ingredientsDetail.name: Inositol

ingredientsDetail.description: Isomalt is a manmade sugar alcohol that is derived from sugar and is used commercially as a sugar substitute. Isomalt has a similar texture and appearance to sugar so is commonly used in cake decorating, but it is also found in foods like chewing gums, cough drops, and nutritional supplements. Isomalt is thought to have little to no impact on blood sugar levels. Like other sugar alcohols, isomalt may cause a laxative effect or other GI symptoms such as gas, abdominal pain, and bloating.
ingredientsDetail.name: Isomalt

ingredientsDetail.description: Karaya is a vegetable gum that comes from the sap of trees grown in India. Karaya gum is mostly used in medications but is occasionally used in food processing as a binder or stabilizer. Medicinally, it is used as a bulk forming laxative; therefore, excess doses may cause diarrhea. Because it swells rapidly, karaya gum supplement should be taken with large amounts of water to avoid the possibility of intestinal obstruction.
ingredientsDetail.name: Karaya

ingredientsDetail.description: Konjac gum is derived from the root of the konjac plant. It's mostly used in food manufacturing to thicken processed foods.
ingredientsDetail.name: Konjac gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Lactitol is a sugar alcohol used as a sweetener in calorie reduced and sugar free foods like chewing gum, candies, ice cream, and baked goods. Lactitol tastes similarly to table sugar, but it's only 40% as sweet so it is often blended with other sugar substitutes. It has no effect on glucose levels, which may make it a good alternative to sugar for people with diabetes. Like other sugar alcohols, lactitol may cause a laxative effect or other GI symptoms such as gas and bloating.
ingredientsDetail.name: Lactitol

ingredientsDetail.description: Locust bean gum or carob bean gum comes from the seeds of the carob tree and is often used a thickener in packaged foods.
ingredientsDetail.name: Locust bean carob gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Maltitol is a sugar alcohol made from starches and is used commonly as a sugar substitute in processed foods, including sugar free candies, gums, chocolates, and ice creams. Maltitol may also be added to medications and supplements. Maltitol has fewer calories than sugar, but it can affect blood sugar. Like other sugar alcohols, maltitol may cause a laxative effect or other GI symptoms such as gas and bloating.
ingredientsDetail.name: Maltitol

ingredientsDetail.description: Mannitol is a sugar alcohol that occurs naturally in fruits and vegetables. Commercially prepared mannitol is used a sugar substitute and is found in many foods labeled as "sugar free", including beverages, chewing gums, and protein powders. It also found in medications and supplements. Mannitol may cause a laxative effect or other gastrointestinal symptoms, like bloating or gas. People with sensitive digestive systems, such as IBS or SIBO, may be more prone to experiencing GI side effects even when consuming small quantities.
ingredientsDetail.name: Mannitol

ingredientsDetail.description: Mastic gum is a resin from the mastic tree. It is most commonly used in supplement form and is thought to have antioxidant, antimicrobial, and anti-inflammatory properties. Studies have found that it may be beneficial in treating H. Pylori, peptic ulcers, and IBD, preventing dental cavities, and lowering cholesterol.
ingredientsDetail.name: Mastic gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Parabens are synthetic additives used widely in processed foods to prevent spoilage. They can be found in many baked goods, trail mixes, and dried meats, and they are also used in cosmetics and medications.
ingredientsDetail.name: Methylparaben

ingredientsDetail.description: Monk fruit, or luo han guo, is a natural sweetener and sugar substitute from Southeast Asia. It has no carbohydrates and does not affect blood glucose levels, so it may be a safe alternative to sugar for diabetics. It is also popular in keto diets. Monk fruit is approximately 100-250 times sweeter than sugar, so it is often mixed with a sugar alcohol, such as erythritol, to reduce the intensity and more closely match the flavor of sugar.
ingredientsDetail.name: Monk fruit

ingredientsDetail.description: MSG or monosodium glutamate is a flavor enhancer commonly added to canned goods and processed meats.
ingredientsDetail.name: Monosodium glutamate

ingredientsDetail.description: Natural flavors are flavor blends created by food manufacturers. They can be made from animal or plant sources including spices, fruits, vegetables, juices, yeast, herbs, dairy products, meat, poultry, seafood, eggs, bark, buds, root leaves, or plant material. The only way to determine specific ingredients in natural flavors is to contact the food manufacturer. Fig is calling on manufacturers to tell us every ingredient. Sign the pledge at everyingredient.org.
ingredientsDetail.name: Natural and artificial flavor

ingredientsDetail.description: Natural flavors are flavor blends created by food manufacturers. They can be made from animal or plant sources including spices, fruits, vegetables, juices, yeast, herbs, dairy products, meat, poultry, seafood, eggs, bark, buds, root leaves, or plant material. The only way to determine specific ingredients in natural flavors is to contact the food manufacturer. Fig is calling on manufacturers to tell us every ingredient. Sign the pledge at everyingredient.org.
ingredientsDetail.name: Natural flavors

ingredientsDetail.description: Polyglycitol is a sugar alcohol that is used commerically as an artifical sweetener and bulking agent. It can be found in foods such as baked goods, breakfast cereals, and pastries. Polyglycitol may cause a laxative effect in large quantities. People with sensitive digestive systems, such as IBS or SIBO, may be more prone to experiencing GI side effects even when consuming small quantities.
ingredientsDetail.name: Polyglycitol

ingredientsDetail.description: Potassium bromate, also listed as "bromated flour, is used as a dough conditioner in baked goods, breads, and pizza doughs. Potassium bromate helps dough rise higher, bleaches the dough to keep it white in color, and keeps the final product looking fresh.
ingredientsDetail.name: Potassium bromate

ingredientsDetail.description: Parabens are synthetic additives used widely in processed foods to prevent spoilage. They can be found in many baked goods, trail mixes, and dried meats, and they are also used in cosmetics and medications. Parabens are thought to affect reproduction and act as endocrine disruptors in animals (which may cause breast cancer), but there is a lack of evidence to link parabens to cancer or other health problems in humans.
ingredientsDetail.name: Propylparaben

ingredientsDetail.description: Red #3 is a synthetic dye banned for cosmetic use but is used in processed foods including maraschino cherries, sausage casings, popsicles, and candy.
ingredientsDetail.name: Red #3

ingredientsDetail.description: Red #40 is a synthetic dye used for coloring in processed foods like popsicles, ice cream, flavored milks, gelatin, and cereals.
ingredientsDetail.name: Red #40

ingredientsDetail.description: Saccharin, also known as Sweet N' Low, was discovered in the late 1870s and is the oldest no calorie artificial sweetener. It is 200-700 times sweeter than sugar and is often mixed with other artificial sweeteners due to its bitter aftertaste.
ingredientsDetail.name: Saccharin

ingredientsDetail.description: Please review the ingredient and allergen statements carefully to determine which shellfish are in or cross-contaminated with this product.
ingredientsDetail.name: Shellfish

ingredientsDetail.description: Sodium benzoate is a preservative, commonly used in acidic foods and sodas.
ingredientsDetail.name: Sodium benzoate

ingredientsDetail.description: Nitrates and nitrites are types of salt commonly used as preservatives in processed meats.
ingredientsDetail.name: Sodium nitrate

ingredientsDetail.description: Nitrates and nitrites are types of salt commonly used as preservatives in processed meats.
ingredientsDetail.name: Sodium nitrite

ingredientsDetail.description: Sorbitol is a sugar alcohol used as an artificial sweetener in processed foods. Sorbitol also occurs naturally in some fruits. Sorbitol is commonly added to sugar free chewing gums as well as reduced calorie baked goods and desserts. Sorbitol may also be added to medications and supplements. Like other sugar alcohols, sorbitol may cause a laxative effect or other gastrointestinal symptoms, such as bloating or gas.
ingredientsDetail.name: Sorbitol

ingredientsDetail.description: Stevia is a natural sweetener and sugar substitute derived from the Stevia rebaudiana plant. Stevia is 200-300 times sweeter than sugar and has zero calories. It has no effect on blood glucose levels, so it may be a safe alternative to table sugar for people with diabetes.
ingredientsDetail.name: Stevia

ingredientsDetail.description: Sucralose, also known as Splenda, is an artificial sweetener 400-700 times sweeter than sugar. It is possible that sucralose may impact blood sugar levels, so caution is advised for use in diabetics.
ingredientsDetail.name: Sucralose (splenda)

ingredientsDetail.description: Sulfites can be added to food as an antioxidant preservative or may be found naturally in foods like wine, beer, or juices.
ingredientsDetail.name: Sulfites

ingredientsDetail.description: Tara gum is derived from the seeds of the tara tree. It is commonly used in conjuction with other gums as a thickener and stabilizer in packaged foods like jellies, frozen foods, and ice cream.
ingredientsDetail.name: Tara gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Tragacanth is natural gum that comes from a Middle Eastern plant. It is most often used as a stabilizer and thickener in processed foods and is commonly found in salad dressings, condiments, and relishes.
ingredientsDetail.name: Tragacanth

ingredientsDetail.description: Natural flavors are flavor blends created by food manufacturers. They can be made from animal or plant sources including spices, fruits, vegetables, juices, yeast, herbs, dairy products, meat, poultry, seafood, eggs, bark, buds, root leaves, or plant material. The only way to determine specific ingredients in natural flavors is to contact the food manufacturer. Fig is calling on manufacturers to tell us every ingredient. Sign the pledge at everyingredient.org.
ingredientsDetail.name: Vegan natural flavor

ingredientsDetail.description: Vegetable gums are often used by food manufacturers as thickeners in processed foods. Typically when vegetable gums are listed on a food label it is referring to locust bean, xanthan, or guar gum.
ingredientsDetail.name: Vegetable gums

ingredientsDetail.description: Xanthan gum is an indigestible carbohydrate commonly used as an emulsifier and thickener in processed foods like sauces, salad dressings, and ice cream. Xanthan gum is popular in gluten free baked goods because it acts similarly to gluten, improving texture and binding ingredients together. It may cause digestive distress in sensitive individuals with IBS/SIBO or when consumed in large quantities.
ingredientsDetail.name: Xanthan gum

ingredientsDetail.description: Xylitol is a naturally occurring sugar alcohol found in low levels in fruits and vegetables. Commercially prepared xylitol is used in higher amounts as a sugar substitute. It is commonly found in gum, toothpastes, mouthwashes, and sugar free candies. Large amounts of xylitol may cause a laxative effect, though people with sensitive digestive systems, such as IBS or SIBO, may be more prone to GI side effects even when consuming small quantities.
ingredientsDetail.name: Xylitol

ingredientsDetail.description: Yellow #5 is a synthetic dye used in processed foods including cereals, pastries, sodas, pickles, and candy.
ingredientsDetail.name: Yellow #5

ingredientsDetail.description: Yellow #6 is a synthetic food dye used in processed foods including hot chocolate mixes, crackers, bouillon, sausages, candies, and gelatins.
ingredientsDetail.name: Yellow #6

ingredientsDetail.description: Cellulose gum is a complex carbohydrate used as a thickener and is commonly found in cheese products and medications/supplements. Cellulose occurs naturally in plant foods and is the main constituent of cell walls in plants. Cellulose gum, commonly made from wood pulp and used as a food additive, may contribute to GI symptoms in individuals with sensitive digestive systems, such as IBS or SIBO.
ingredientsDetail.name: Cellulose gum
